> +// A PCollection!
> +message PCollection {
> +

> +  int64 id = 1;

> +  // (Required) A unique program-readable name for the value, such as

> +  string label = 2;
> +
> +  // (Required) The id of the Coder for this PCollection.
> +  int64 coder_ref = 3;

> +  // (Required) Whether this PCollection is bounded or unbounded
> +  IsBounded is_bounded = 4;

> This falls into the category of "things that could be inferred, but I'd
> like the SDK to do so". I think windowing strategy is also in this bucket -
> there are rules for how it is expected to propagate, but the SDK is the one
> tasked with implementing those rules.
>
> I guess the main thing a runner does with this information is figure out
> (a) if it can run the pipeline and (b) how to partition a pipeline into
> bits that can run batch style versus streaming style. These can probably be
> done via other means like just looking at Reads and SDFs. Do you have
> something in mind?
>
> Another reason it is here is that it is a field on Java's PCollection
> object that runners do inspect IIRC. And in a (wildly imagined)
> mix-and-match scenario a transform might be receiving an input that came
> from a deserialized pipeline fragment.
>

Is it an invalid graph if the SDK doesn't properly infer things like this
(e.g. windowing in == windowing out for non window-into transforms).
Possibly one could have a "normalize" pass over the graph that would do
this inference, so neither N SDKs nor M runners would have to do it.

I'm OK with required for now, possibly relaxing it later (always populating
it before a runner gets it).

> In the Runner API, this will be the Any payload on the generic GraphNode,

I'm not following why the discrepancy. Either this should always be a
PTransform (in which case there's a 1:1 relationship between PTransforms
and GraphNodes, and we could collapse them) or there's a choice (based on
the semantics of the graph, not whether this is being used for Runner or Fn
API) to make here.

>
> The same reason it is an enum - we envision perhaps a list of contextual
> requirements. Just an example we won't follow - today in the DataflowRunner
> we have USES_KEYED_STATE as well as REQUIRES_WINDOW_ACCESS.
>
> I guess there is probably an idiomatic way to leave it singular and evolve

> Two commits ago it was just a bool requires_window_access so I'm not
> terribly attached to it, except that the signature of the DoFn as it
> pertains to the runner needs to be indicated here.

It almost feels like this should be a generic map of attributes that the
runner might want to inspect. Not all of them may be bools (e.g. what states
are used).

> +  // language-to-language fusion compatibility) or by the runner directly.
> +  string urn = 2;
> +
> +  // (Required) Reference to the specification of the execution environment
> +  // required to invoke this function.
> +  int64 environment_reference = 3;
> +
> +  // (Optional) If present, a payload whose schema is determined by the URN of
> +  // this function.
> +  google.protobuf.Any payload = 4;
> +
> +  // (Required) The raw data of the function that the SDK knows how to
>
> My favorite example is the WindowFn for FixedWindows.
>
>    - URN is urn:beam:windowfn:fixedwindows
>    - Payload is a published proto/other containing {duration: ...}
>    - Data is where there's serialized Java / pickled Python
>
> You may say that the Java SDK should simply reconstruct its FixedWindows
> from the URN and the payload,
>
Exactly.

> but I like the ability to be fluid about which things actually have a
> payload adequate to specify them. For things we want to share, we clearly
> need a runner-grokkable payload. For things we don't want to share, we
> clearly need an SDK-specific blob. Does that make sense? The part of this
> that is new is the payload, otherwise the URN is just often not that
> useful.
>
We should strive to reduce ambiguity and redundancy. If both the payload
and data are specified, which should the runner use? What if they don't
agree? In all graphs, one needs a payload XOR a data.

If the URN is something the runner doesn't understand, the payload is an
opaque (often SDK-specific) blob, which may be the serialized bytes
sufficient to adequately specify it. This is handled by having SDK-specific
namespaces for the URNs.
